1
00:01:58,109 --> 00:02:00,009
You coming or not?

2
00:03:37,875 --> 00:03:41,311
- All right, I'll get her to you right away.
- Appreciate it.

3
00:03:42,513 --> 00:03:43,537
- Hi.
- Hi.

4
00:03:43,781 --> 00:03:48,013
<i>Dr. Klyczynski to ER, stat.
Dr. Klyczynski to ER, stat.</i>

5
00:03:48,252 --> 00:03:51,551
- Hi, excuse me.
- Yeah, just a minute, okay?

6
00:03:52,823 --> 00:03:56,281
- Fill this out for me and wait over there.
- No, I'm... I'm Dr. Forster.

7
00:03:56,493 --> 00:03:57,824
I was told to report here.

8
00:03:57,995 --> 00:04:01,453
You'll be covering 22 patients
on rounds today, this floor and the next.

9
00:04:01,665 --> 00:04:03,292
- Twenty-two?
- Quiet morning.

10
00:04:03,500 --> 00:04:06,367
If you get into trouble, beep me,
but don't make it a habit.

11
00:04:06,570 --> 00:04:09,061
The med students
will help you out with scutwork.

12
00:04:09,273 --> 00:04:12,003
What's he doing here?
I ordered an MRI, stat.

13
00:04:12,209 --> 00:04:15,770
- Transport said about four hours.
- He could be dead in four hours.

14
00:04:15,980 --> 00:04:18,175
Never mind. Dr. Forster, MRI.

15
00:04:18,349 --> 00:04:20,408
- A right, two lefts, elevator to two.
- Okay.

16
00:04:20,651 --> 00:04:23,051
Follow the signs.
Hustle back here for rounds.

17
00:04:24,021 --> 00:04:25,716
Dr. Kly...

18
00:04:27,358 --> 00:04:30,816
- Are you taking me somewhere?
- I certainly hope so, sir.

19
00:04:31,028 --> 00:04:33,792
- How are you feeling today?
- Am...? Am I gonna make it?

20
00:04:34,598 --> 00:04:36,691
Yes. Absolutely.

21
00:04:40,904 --> 00:04:42,804
Alex!

22
00:04:43,007 --> 00:04:47,341
I made my famous spinach pie.
The trailer's nice and toasty.

23
00:04:47,544 --> 00:04:49,409
I can't.

24
00:04:51,915 --> 00:04:55,874
Look, it's really cold out here.
Don't get sick on me or anything.

25
00:04:56,086 --> 00:04:58,577
I never get sick.

26
00:04:59,323 --> 00:05:03,521
So I heard you bought a house,
and apparently I'm the last one to know.

27
00:05:03,727 --> 00:05:05,126
I thought I mentioned that.

28
00:05:05,362 --> 00:05:07,057
Wait.

29
00:05:07,731 --> 00:05:09,028
Where?

30
00:05:09,233 --> 00:05:11,531
Outside of town.
Up the shore a little bit.

31
00:05:11,735 --> 00:05:13,430
Up the shore? There's no houses...

32
00:05:13,637 --> 00:05:17,573
Oh, God. You don't mean that thing
with the stilts and the...?

33
00:05:20,210 --> 00:05:23,543
- You all right?
- Yeah. Are you crazy?

34
00:05:24,882 --> 00:05:27,578
Why would you take that house, Alex?

35
00:05:27,785 --> 00:05:30,447
It's made of glass. There's no privacy.

36
00:05:30,654 --> 00:05:32,315
Mona?

37
00:05:32,756 --> 00:05:35,054
Get yourself some boots.

38
00:05:37,861 --> 00:05:40,056
Hey, Gonzalez!

39
00:05:44,868 --> 00:05:46,802
- Four-thirty.
- You lost?

40
00:05:47,004 --> 00:05:50,064
- Yeah.
- Takes a while to get your bearings.

41
00:05:50,274 --> 00:05:53,402
- I'm Madhvi.
- Kate Forster. Hi.

42
00:05:53,610 --> 00:05:57,011
Oh, wrong floor.
Where'd you do your residency?

43
00:05:57,247 --> 00:06:00,011
Just a little community hospital
up on the North Shore.

44
00:06:20,771 --> 00:06:24,207
<i>Dear new tenant,
welcome to your new home.</i>

45
00:06:24,441 --> 00:06:26,170
<i>As the previous tenant, let me say...</i>

46
00:06:26,410 --> 00:06:29,345
<i>... I hope you'll like living here
as much as I did.</i>

47
00:06:29,546 --> 00:06:32,640
<i>I filed the change of address
with the post office...</i>

48
00:06:32,850 --> 00:06:35,182
<i>... but you know
what a crapshoot that can be.</i>

49
00:06:35,419 --> 00:06:39,048
<i>So if anything slips through, would you
do me a favor and forward my mail?</i>

50
00:06:39,289 --> 00:06:42,952
<i>I'd appreciate it.
My new address is below.</i>

51
00:06:43,160 --> 00:06:46,994
<i>Thanks in advance. P. S:</i>

52
00:06:47,197 --> 00:06:51,691
"Sorry about the paw prints by the front
door. They were there when I moved in.

53
00:06:52,169 --> 00:06:55,195
Same with the box in the attic."

54
00:06:57,040 --> 00:07:01,306
Paw prints?
What the hell is she talking about?

55
00:07:15,392 --> 00:07:18,828
Hey, baby girl. Hi. Hi. Hey.

56
00:07:29,973 --> 00:07:32,066
Fix the light.

57
00:07:33,076 --> 00:07:35,203
Get dog food, huh?

58
00:07:36,246 --> 00:07:38,180
Get human food.

59
00:08:06,543 --> 00:08:09,740
Hey. Hey.

60
00:08:14,618 --> 00:08:16,779
Hey, come here.

61
00:08:25,896 --> 00:08:29,923
Sixty degrees on Valentine's Day.
Can't be Chicago.

62
00:08:30,133 --> 00:08:32,499
The TV says it's global warming.

63
00:08:32,669 --> 00:08:36,469
The icebergs start melting,
water covers the Earth.

64
00:08:36,673 --> 00:08:39,335
Thank God we won't live to see it.

65
00:08:40,744 --> 00:08:42,177
What's this?

66
00:08:42,980 --> 00:08:44,948
That's nothing.
It's one of your father's.

67
00:08:45,148 --> 00:08:48,584
- Dostoyevsky?
- Oh, yeah.

68
00:08:48,919 --> 00:08:55,256
It's about a guy who breaks the neck
of a poor woman with an axe...

69
00:08:55,459 --> 00:08:59,259
...and, so far, keeps wandering
around regretting it.

70
00:09:02,599 --> 00:09:04,066
This is good.

71
00:09:04,268 --> 00:09:07,669
- Oh, yeah?
- Yeah. It's really good.

72
00:09:08,872 --> 00:09:09,861
I'll meet you there.

73
00:09:10,107 --> 00:09:11,472
What are you thinking?

74
00:09:11,975 --> 00:09:13,374
My folks are coming into town.

75
00:09:13,610 --> 00:09:15,271
Nothing.

76
00:09:15,479 --> 00:09:19,711
When your father passed away,
it was hard. It still is hard.

77
00:09:19,883 --> 00:09:24,820
Holding his books,
I feel like he's with me somehow.

78
00:09:25,022 --> 00:09:27,786
Knowing that he was once
on the same pages...

79
00:09:27,991 --> 00:09:30,152
...reading the same words.

80
00:09:35,399 --> 00:09:38,994
Oh, my God!
Somebody call an ambulance!

81
00:09:39,703 --> 00:09:41,364
We need an ambulance at Daley Plaza.

82
00:09:41,605 --> 00:09:44,540
A man has been struck by a bus.
Get an EMT crew here. Sir...

83
00:09:44,741 --> 00:09:46,606
Get out the street.
Get on the sidewalk.

84
00:09:46,810 --> 00:09:48,607
- On the sidewalk. Off the street.
- Sir?

85
00:09:48,812 --> 00:09:51,337
Get on the sidewalk!
Get on the sidewalk!

86
00:09:51,515 --> 00:09:54,814
I'd like to get the foundation
on number 17 dug today.

87
00:09:55,419 --> 00:09:58,183
Look, I know you're
kind of new around here, kid.

88
00:09:58,388 --> 00:10:00,015
What?

89
00:10:00,223 --> 00:10:03,351
I can't get to 17 until
at least next week.

90
00:10:03,560 --> 00:10:06,552
Come on, Mulhern.
That's bullshit and you know it.

91
00:10:06,763 --> 00:10:09,061
Take Clemens and Rodriguez
off of roofing.

92
00:10:09,266 --> 00:10:11,928
Jorge can run the backhoe
they're not using on 14...

93
00:10:12,169 --> 00:10:14,330
...and grab four or five
of those other guys...

94
00:10:14,538 --> 00:10:16,836
...who are doing nothing
on seven and 10.

95
00:10:17,040 --> 00:10:20,635
Paulie, Carlos, Frank, Danny,
and what's-his-name, the tall guy?

96
00:10:20,844 --> 00:10:23,335
- Rafael.
- Rafael.

97
00:10:23,547 --> 00:10:26,345
- Let's go.
- Okay.

98
00:10:26,550 --> 00:10:28,074
- Ready?
- Yeah.

99
00:10:28,285 --> 00:10:30,617
- Well, I need it to 10 and 11.
- Hey!

100
00:10:34,224 --> 00:10:37,091
<i>Housekeeping ER
to the Suture Room, please.</i>

101
00:10:37,294 --> 00:10:40,786
<i>Housekeeping ER to the Suture Room.</i>

102
00:10:43,734 --> 00:10:46,396
- Hey.
- Hi.

103
00:10:46,603 --> 00:10:49,436
I heard about Daley Plaza.

104
00:10:50,307 --> 00:10:52,969
EMT said you fought hard for the guy.

105
00:10:53,443 --> 00:10:56,378
Yeah. Really knocked myself out.

106
00:10:57,047 --> 00:11:01,108
<i>Kate, I'm going to tell you
what I tell every young doctor.</i>

107
00:11:01,318 --> 00:11:04,310
<i>Hopefully, you'll be the first to listen.</i>

108
00:11:05,055 --> 00:11:10,220
<i>On your day off, get as far away
from this place as you can.</i>

109
00:11:10,427 --> 00:11:15,729
<i>Go someplace where you feel
most like yourself.</i>

110
00:12:10,620 --> 00:12:12,747
<i>Dear Ms. Forster:</i>

111
00:12:12,956 --> 00:12:14,287
<i>I got your note...</i>

112
00:12:14,491 --> 00:12:17,756
<i>... and I'm afraid there must be
some kind of misunderstanding.</i>

113
00:12:17,961 --> 00:12:21,897
<i>As far as I know, the lake house
has been empty for several years.</i>

114
00:12:22,132 --> 00:12:25,659
<i>Maybe your note was intended for
the Sandburg house down the shore...</i>

115
00:12:25,869 --> 00:12:29,361
"...since no one has lived
in this house for years.

116
00:12:30,373 --> 00:12:33,501
But I'm curious about the paw prints."

117
00:12:39,349 --> 00:12:42,477
<i>Dear Mr. Wyler, I'm very familiar
with the Sandburg cottage...</i>

118
00:12:42,686 --> 00:12:45,211
<i>... and I can guarantee
I never lived there.</i>

119
00:12:45,422 --> 00:12:49,188
<i>I'm old-fashioned, but I don't think a
cottage should be over 6000 square feet.</i>

120
00:12:49,392 --> 00:12:51,360
<i>So let me try again.</i>

121
00:12:51,561 --> 00:12:54,724
<i>I used to live at the lake house,
then I moved.</i>

122
00:12:54,931 --> 00:12:58,560
<i>Now I live at 1620 North Racine
in Chicago.</i>

123
00:12:58,802 --> 00:13:01,828
<i>I'd appreciate it if you would
forward my mail if you get any.</i>

124
00:13:02,038 --> 00:13:05,804
<i>Oh, by the way, it's 2006.</i>

125
00:13:06,009 --> 00:13:08,603
<i>Has been all year, ask anyone.</i>

126
00:13:08,845 --> 00:13:11,313
2006?

127
00:13:11,882 --> 00:13:14,214
What does she mean, 2006?

128
00:13:14,885 --> 00:13:16,853
God.

129
00:13:17,120 --> 00:13:18,109
Oh, God.

130
00:13:21,258 --> 00:13:23,419
- Good morning, Mr. Wyler.
- Morning, Mr. Wyler.

131
00:13:23,627 --> 00:13:25,117
- Morning, sir.
- Morning, morning.

132
00:13:25,362 --> 00:13:27,125
Hello, Mr. Wyler.

133
00:13:27,631 --> 00:13:29,599
Mr. Wyler.

134
00:13:30,400 --> 00:13:32,265
Sir.

135
00:13:34,538 --> 00:13:37,701
Well, obviously,
I derived my inspiration...

136
00:13:37,908 --> 00:13:41,139
...for the metaphor
of the fugue, the loop...

137
00:13:42,979 --> 00:13:44,640
Yeah.

138
00:14:04,467 --> 00:14:07,766
- Two hours of that shit. You kidding me?
- What are you talking about?

139
00:14:07,971 --> 00:14:12,499
- He didn't say a word.
- Sadistic, bitter, bitter old man.

140
00:14:12,742 --> 00:14:15,677
I think you're being
a little overdramatic.

141
00:14:19,516 --> 00:14:21,313
Where are you going?

142
00:14:30,126 --> 00:14:32,458
Man, I love that place.

143
00:14:53,817 --> 00:14:56,650
I can't believe that thing's
still running.

144
00:14:59,656 --> 00:15:01,283
Yep.

145
00:15:02,626 --> 00:15:04,025
You look like shit.

146
00:15:04,861 --> 00:15:06,658
I missed you too.

147
00:15:25,482 --> 00:15:27,712
Hey, forget about him.

148
00:15:32,188 --> 00:15:34,213
- Condos.
- Riviera Estates.

149
00:15:34,457 --> 00:15:36,220
- You're joking.
- I don't believe this.

150
00:15:36,459 --> 00:15:38,256
I come back after four years...

151
00:15:38,495 --> 00:15:40,360
...and I get this in front of me.
- What?

152
00:15:40,563 --> 00:15:42,690
My brother thinking
he's Frank Lloyd Whatever.

153
00:15:42,899 --> 00:15:44,867
- Oh, come on.
- Dad keeps you hostage...

154
00:15:45,068 --> 00:15:47,764
...in that little
mythmaking factory of his...

155
00:15:48,004 --> 00:15:51,337
...while you haven't built so much as
a phone booth or a hamster cage.

156
00:15:51,508 --> 00:15:53,203
That's funny you say that, actually.

157
00:15:53,410 --> 00:15:56,470
I have a hamster cage in mind.
A development of them, actually.

158
00:15:56,680 --> 00:15:59,843
Prefab, no foundations.
What do you think about that?

159
00:16:00,050 --> 00:16:03,247
See, that's what I'm talking about.
You have vision.

160
00:16:04,354 --> 00:16:06,117
Speaking of which...

161
00:16:06,356 --> 00:16:09,621
...l'd like you to know
I bought a house.

162
00:16:09,793 --> 00:16:11,852
- Where?
- On the lake.

163
00:16:12,262 --> 00:16:14,230
A lake house.
So you are making some money.

164
00:16:14,397 --> 00:16:16,888
Well, it's a dump.
Been abandoned for years, but...

165
00:16:17,100 --> 00:16:19,364
So you got an abandoned,
haunted lake hou...

166
00:16:19,569 --> 00:16:21,127
That's as good a reason as any...

167
00:16:21,371 --> 00:16:24,135
...for selling out and joining
the flabby-developers' guild.

168
00:16:24,374 --> 00:16:27,741
- How about this? I even got a dog.
- You got a dog?

169
00:16:28,945 --> 00:16:33,712
He just showed up at the house
from out of nowhere.

170
00:16:45,762 --> 00:16:48,458
- What are we doing here?
- I have to deliver a letter.

171
00:16:48,665 --> 00:16:53,102
It should be here.
1620 North Racine.

172
00:16:56,439 --> 00:16:58,100
But...

173
00:16:59,442 --> 00:17:00,670
...there's nothing here.

174
00:17:02,846 --> 00:17:06,077
Are we meeting someone?
Does somebody live here? What?

175
00:17:06,483 --> 00:17:08,178
Yeah.

176
00:17:08,418 --> 00:17:10,613
I thought so.

177
00:17:11,021 --> 00:17:12,249
Should we ring the bell?

178
00:17:31,207 --> 00:17:32,868
<i>Dear Ms. Forster:</i>

179
00:17:33,109 --> 00:17:36,806
<i>I went to 1620 North Racine,
and it's not there.</i>

180
00:17:37,213 --> 00:17:39,204
<i>It's just a construction site.</i>

181
00:17:39,449 --> 00:17:43,510
<i>From the pictures it looks nice,
but not for another 18 months.</i>

182
00:17:43,720 --> 00:17:45,688
<i>What am I missing here?</i>

183
00:17:45,889 --> 00:17:49,381
<i>Maybe you got the address wrong,
because you got the date wrong too.</i>

184
00:17:49,626 --> 00:17:52,459
You really wanna play this game.

185
00:17:53,296 --> 00:17:58,598
If you are truly in the year 2004...

186
00:17:59,302 --> 00:18:01,600
...then...

187
00:18:03,873 --> 00:18:05,966
...be forewarned.

188
00:18:07,710 --> 00:18:12,238
Remember that day?
You were not happy. Remember that?

189
00:18:13,416 --> 00:18:14,644
I know.

190
00:18:15,251 --> 00:18:18,186
<i>Okay, my mystery correspondent,
I get it.</i>

191
00:18:18,388 --> 00:18:21,755
<i>Just in case you really are
where and when you think you are...</i>

192
00:18:21,991 --> 00:18:23,549
<i>... you'll need this.</i>

193
00:18:23,760 --> 00:18:27,059
<i>There was a freak late snow that spring
and everyone got sick.</i>

194
00:18:27,263 --> 00:18:31,893
<i>So plenty of rest, lots of fluids.
Doctor's orders.</i>

195
00:18:32,135 --> 00:18:35,002
Snow. Right.

196
00:18:39,676 --> 00:18:42,645
Yeah, come to papa.

197
00:20:18,942 --> 00:20:20,671
Jackie.

198
00:20:21,844 --> 00:20:23,607
Jack.

199
00:20:24,013 --> 00:20:27,141
Jack, come on. Come on, girl.
Come on, come on. Jack.

200
00:21:13,429 --> 00:21:16,557
"Impossible, I know. Not possible...

201
00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:18,991
...but it's happening."

202
00:21:29,379 --> 00:21:31,176
Okay.

203
00:21:35,418 --> 00:21:37,113
Where am I?

204
00:21:41,924 --> 00:21:44,051
Very clever.

205
00:21:46,062 --> 00:21:48,087
"The lake house."

206
00:21:48,531 --> 00:21:51,523
The lake house. As you can see,
I, too, am at the lake house...

207
00:21:51,701 --> 00:21:54,864
...but I'm getting tired of these games
so I'm leaving, okay? Bye.

208
00:21:55,038 --> 00:21:56,266
Thank you. Bye.

209
00:21:58,841 --> 00:22:02,038
Maybe we should
introduce ourselves properly.

210
00:22:06,716 --> 00:22:10,584
<i>I'm a doctor,
dedicated to curing the sick.</i>

211
00:22:10,953 --> 00:22:12,648
<i>At least, trying to.</i>

212
00:22:13,790 --> 00:22:16,122
<i>I'm an architect. I like to build.</i>

213
00:22:16,359 --> 00:22:19,157
<i>And while I wouldn't say
my current project is ideal...</i>

214
00:22:19,395 --> 00:22:24,458
<i>... it allows me to be here, in this place,
and that's enough for now.</i>

215
00:22:24,801 --> 00:22:28,760
<i>But tell me something. If you're working
in a hospital in Chicago now...</i>

216
00:22:28,971 --> 00:22:31,906
<i>... where were you before, in my time?</i>

217
00:22:32,675 --> 00:22:34,302
<i>Two years ago, in your time...</i>

218
00:22:34,510 --> 00:22:38,606
<i>... I was working
in internal medicine in Madison.</i>

219
00:22:41,651 --> 00:22:42,948
<i>Tell me about the future.</i>

220
00:22:43,953 --> 00:22:46,683
<i>What's it like in the year 2006?</i>

221
00:22:48,024 --> 00:22:50,754
<i>I'm afraid the world's
pretty much the same.</i>

222
00:22:51,961 --> 00:22:55,954
<i>Of course, we all dress in shiny metal
jump suits and drive flying cars...</i>

223
00:22:56,165 --> 00:22:59,896
<i>... and no one talks anymore
because we can read each other's minds.</i>

224
00:23:00,103 --> 00:23:03,197
<i>But the truth is, man from the past...</i>

225
00:23:03,439 --> 00:23:06,966
<i>... not much has really changed
in 2006.</i>

226
00:23:08,778 --> 00:23:12,475
<i>Speaking of the past, though,
I've been thinking about the paw prints.</i>

227
00:23:12,682 --> 00:23:16,880
<i>- How is that possible?
- Well, I think we have the same dog.</i>

228
00:23:17,653 --> 00:23:20,178
<i>Oh, yeah? What's yours like?</i>

229
00:23:20,423 --> 00:23:24,189
<i>According to the vet,
mine is eight years old in my time...</i>

230
00:23:24,427 --> 00:23:26,418
<i>...six in yours.</i>

231
00:23:26,929 --> 00:23:32,424
<i>She's skinny, has sad eyes, snores,
and sleeps like a person.</i>

232
00:23:32,635 --> 00:23:34,933
<i>I don't know why, but I call her Jack.</i>

233
00:23:35,138 --> 00:23:37,129
Hello, Jack.

234
00:23:40,309 --> 00:23:42,869
<i>It's nice out here.</i>

235
00:23:43,146 --> 00:23:46,377
<i>Let's not go out for dinner.
Let's stay here.</i>

236
00:23:46,582 --> 00:23:48,516
<i>- Hey.
- We have to eat.</i>

237
00:23:48,718 --> 00:23:51,312
What are you doing?
You're supposed to be asleep.

238
00:23:51,687 --> 00:23:52,881
<i>I'll cook.</i>

239
00:23:53,823 --> 00:23:55,950
<i>I thought you didn't like to cook.</i>

240
00:23:56,659 --> 00:23:58,854
<i>No, I don't like to cook.</i>

241
00:23:59,061 --> 00:24:01,086
Is she gonna marry him?

242
00:24:01,264 --> 00:24:04,893
- What do you think?
- I don't know. He's kind of old.

243
00:24:05,067 --> 00:24:08,264
<i>- Where are you going?
- Okay, he's not that old.</i>

244
00:24:08,838 --> 00:24:10,669
My mom's last boyfriend was bald.

245
00:24:11,374 --> 00:24:12,773
He was nice...

246
00:24:12,942 --> 00:24:15,740
...but my mom didn't marry him.
- No?

247
00:24:15,978 --> 00:24:18,845
"There's always something better
coming around the corner."

248
00:24:19,048 --> 00:24:21,414
That's what she says.

249
00:24:21,851 --> 00:24:25,412
Maybe that's what that lady should do.
Wait for something better...

250
00:24:25,621 --> 00:24:28,590
...to come around the corner.
- Maybe.

251
00:24:30,593 --> 00:24:34,359
But if she's not careful,
she could spend her whole life waiting.

252
00:24:35,298 --> 00:24:37,630
<i>Do you want me to bring
anything back with me?</i>

253
00:24:37,800 --> 00:24:40,428
<i>Yes. What about
a nice bottle of wine...</i>

254
00:24:41,204 --> 00:24:42,762
<i>... to celebrate?</i>

255
00:24:43,005 --> 00:24:46,031
<i>- What time shall I come back?
- Seven o'clock.</i>

256
00:24:46,242 --> 00:24:49,006
<i>Sorry I haven't made it
to the mailbox lately.</i>

257
00:24:49,212 --> 00:24:53,148
<i>It's been a long week. All night shifts.</i>

258
00:24:53,416 --> 00:24:56,510
<i>Good to hear from you.
I thought you left me.</i>

259
00:24:56,719 --> 00:25:00,450
<i>You should know that you're
my only connection to the future.</i>

260
00:25:01,090 --> 00:25:04,321
<i>How come we never talk
about the things we like?</i>

261
00:25:04,660 --> 00:25:08,152
<i>Well, let's see.
Reading the classics to Jack.</i>

262
00:25:08,397 --> 00:25:11,525
<i>- Who's his favorite?
- Dostoyevsky.</i>

263
00:25:11,734 --> 00:25:15,397
<i>For me, this city,
on a day when the light is so clear...</i>

264
00:25:15,605 --> 00:25:17,232
<i>... that I can touch every detail...</i>

265
00:25:17,440 --> 00:25:20,102
<i>... every brick and window
in the buildings I love.</i>

266
00:25:20,309 --> 00:25:24,905
<i>Come on, take a walk with me
this Saturday. Let me show you.</i>

267
00:25:25,114 --> 00:25:28,550
<i>You're crazy. Why are you going
through all this trouble for me?</i>

268
00:25:28,751 --> 00:25:31,777
<i>No trouble. Summer's here.</i>

269
00:25:44,433 --> 00:25:48,096
<i>Okay, your turn. Favorite things.</i>

270
00:25:48,304 --> 00:25:51,137
<i>Where to start? Okay.</i>

271
00:25:51,340 --> 00:25:54,434
<i>When I smell the flowers
before I see them.</i>

272
00:25:54,644 --> 00:25:58,944
<i>When it starts to rain
just as the picnic is ending.</i>

273
00:25:59,148 --> 00:26:03,016
<i>And I love the smell of Jack's paws.</i>

274
00:26:03,219 --> 00:26:05,847
<i>You didn't forget
to mention your husband, did you?</i>

275
00:26:06,789 --> 00:26:10,316
<i>Well, of course I love my husband,
who is also a doctor.</i>

276
00:26:10,526 --> 00:26:12,960
<i>Plastic surgeon
for small farm animals.</i>

277
00:26:13,162 --> 00:26:15,460
<i>Good. I'm married too.</i>

278
00:26:15,665 --> 00:26:19,123
<i>I've got eight children,
and none of them look like me.</i>

279
00:26:19,335 --> 00:26:22,498
<i>- I'm worried, Kate.
- I would be too.</i>

280
00:26:22,905 --> 00:26:24,304
<i>I'm single.</i>

281
00:26:25,141 --> 00:26:26,904
<i>Me too.</i>

282
00:26:29,979 --> 00:26:31,810
<i>Number 27.</i>

283
00:26:32,014 --> 00:26:34,175
<i>She's a beauty.
My father used to tell me...</i>

284
00:26:34,383 --> 00:26:37,250
<i>... she was the grandma
for all the houses in the city.</i>

285
00:26:37,486 --> 00:26:40,922
<i>He used to take me on walks
like I'm taking you now.</i>

286
00:26:41,357 --> 00:26:44,622
<i>- Alex?
- Kate?</i>

287
00:26:44,827 --> 00:26:47,660
<i>I wish we could have
done this walk together.</i>

288
00:27:02,745 --> 00:27:04,542
So, what do you think?

289
00:27:04,847 --> 00:27:07,281
He sounds like a nice boy.

290
00:27:07,450 --> 00:27:10,146
Sounds like a nice boy.
Anything else?

291
00:27:10,353 --> 00:27:13,686
- He has wonderful penmanship.
- Mother...

292
00:27:13,856 --> 00:27:16,256
...look at the date on the letter.
The date.

293
00:27:16,459 --> 00:27:17,949
- You mean the time thing?
- Yes.

294
00:27:18,194 --> 00:27:20,788
- That's just a detail.
- Just a detail?

295
00:27:29,872 --> 00:27:32,966
About the...
The other day...

296
00:27:33,209 --> 00:27:38,078
...it was not a good moment.
I was in a hell of a hurry.

297
00:27:38,414 --> 00:27:40,041
Of course.

298
00:27:41,450 --> 00:27:43,611
You've got some nice pieces here.

299
00:27:43,819 --> 00:27:47,619
Oh, yeah. Music's fine, music helps.

300
00:27:48,324 --> 00:27:49,985
It's like Nietzsche says:

301
00:27:50,226 --> 00:27:53,491
- "Life would be senseless..."
- "Without music."

302
00:27:54,397 --> 00:27:56,297
I guess I told you that, huh?

303
00:27:56,499 --> 00:27:57,932
Pour yourself a drink.

304
00:27:58,134 --> 00:28:01,399
Can you appreciate
a good wine by now?

305
00:28:01,604 --> 00:28:03,504
You bet.

306
00:28:04,340 --> 00:28:07,434
You know, you'll have to forgive
your father for being curious...

307
00:28:07,643 --> 00:28:10,806
...but where have you been
all these years?

308
00:28:11,147 --> 00:28:14,412
I thought your Kerouac days
were behind you.

309
00:28:15,418 --> 00:28:18,216
- I'm sorry, what?
- What?

310
00:28:19,455 --> 00:28:21,946
Oh, you can come up, if you like.

311
00:28:30,666 --> 00:28:32,293
What are you working on?

312
00:28:32,468 --> 00:28:35,528
Oh, I'm just...
I'm just remembering things.

313
00:28:35,771 --> 00:28:38,433
It's not such an easy job,
let me tell you.

314
00:28:38,641 --> 00:28:41,610
Nor is it particularly innocent,
in my case.

315
00:28:41,811 --> 00:28:45,178
Your father is writing his memoirs.

316
00:28:46,882 --> 00:28:48,543
- Are we in it?
- What do you think?

317
00:28:48,718 --> 00:28:50,481
Do you wanna be?

318
00:28:51,620 --> 00:28:53,019
Do you?

319
00:28:53,255 --> 00:28:56,850
Of course.
You were all a part of your father's life.

320
00:28:58,127 --> 00:29:00,220
Why are you talking to me
in the third person?

321
00:29:00,396 --> 00:29:02,057
Well, l... I don't...

322
00:29:02,298 --> 00:29:05,631
Because I'm writing about myself,
I suppose. Why, doesn't it suit you?

323
00:29:08,504 --> 00:29:11,996
I thought you might like these.

324
00:29:13,909 --> 00:29:16,207
What are these?
Something you've been working on?

325
00:29:16,412 --> 00:29:19,279
No, they're... They're yours.

326
00:29:19,482 --> 00:29:23,543
From a house I just bought
on the lake.

327
00:29:24,587 --> 00:29:28,318
Oh, yes, I heard. They said
some sleazy little condo developer...

328
00:29:28,524 --> 00:29:30,515
...had snapped it up.

329
00:29:30,893 --> 00:29:34,158
Oh, come on. Indulge your father.

330
00:29:34,363 --> 00:29:37,355
Can't you take a little joke,
for God's sake?

331
00:29:37,700 --> 00:29:39,497
Come on.

332
00:29:39,668 --> 00:29:41,397
Tell me.

333
00:29:41,871 --> 00:29:44,066
Where have you been?
I really want to know.

334
00:29:44,306 --> 00:29:46,797
I was trying to forget you.

335
00:29:48,544 --> 00:29:50,876
Or forgive you.

336
00:29:52,214 --> 00:29:54,375
Did you succeed?

337
00:29:56,685 --> 00:29:58,380
No.

338
00:30:02,725 --> 00:30:05,751
Let me know
if you need any help remembering.

339
00:30:07,763 --> 00:30:10,823
Oh, yeah, I will.

340
00:30:11,600 --> 00:30:15,229
Charging 360. Get 1 milligram of epi.
Have 300 amio ready in case we need it.

341
00:30:15,437 --> 00:30:18,065
- All clear?
- Clear.

342
00:30:20,242 --> 00:30:22,335
Hold compression, start bagging.

343
00:30:22,545 --> 00:30:23,842
He's got a rhythm. Slow.

344
00:30:24,046 --> 00:30:26,640
- Do we have a pulse with that?
- We got a pulse, thready.

345
00:30:26,882 --> 00:30:28,782
<i>- It's getting stronger.
- Long days, these days.</i>

346
00:30:28,984 --> 00:30:31,714
<i>I just worked 30 hours straight.</i>

347
00:30:31,921 --> 00:30:34,412
<i>Every time I stop to take a breath...</i>

348
00:30:34,623 --> 00:30:37,888
<i>... I realize how isolated
I've let myself become.</i>

349
00:30:38,060 --> 00:30:42,997
<i>Believe me,
you can get a bit desperate.</i>

350
00:30:44,633 --> 00:30:47,101
That one? Okay. There you go.

351
00:30:47,303 --> 00:30:51,501
Nice move. Very nice. Nice.

352
00:30:54,143 --> 00:30:57,169
<i>It's not that I'm complaining,
I love my work.</i>

353
00:30:57,413 --> 00:31:01,747
<i>And our tour through Chicago
opened my eyes to its beauty.</i>

354
00:31:01,951 --> 00:31:04,886
<i>But my heart still misses
the lake house...</i>

355
00:31:05,087 --> 00:31:07,282
<i>... and its trees.</i>

356
00:31:08,190 --> 00:31:10,818
<i>I miss those trees so much.</i>

357
00:32:28,070 --> 00:32:31,597
<i>Don't worry, Kate.
We'll be together in time.</i>

358
00:32:31,840 --> 00:32:35,173
<i>Even if we're far apart,
I'll find a way to be close to you...</i>

359
00:32:35,377 --> 00:32:37,402
<i>... and take care of you.</i>

360
00:32:42,785 --> 00:32:44,582
Katerina.

361
00:32:46,021 --> 00:32:47,784
Take this.

362
00:32:48,257 --> 00:32:51,124
- You should eat more. You too skinny.
- I'm not too skinny.

363
00:32:51,293 --> 00:32:54,558
Remember how you used to eat
when you were little?

364
00:32:54,763 --> 00:32:56,492
- With your hands.
- Yes, I remember.

365
00:32:56,699 --> 00:32:59,532
Now, did you or did you not
write to each other?

366
00:32:59,902 --> 00:33:01,802
- To your father?
- No, to Clark Gable.

367
00:33:02,037 --> 00:33:04,631
Yes, to Dad.

368
00:33:07,076 --> 00:33:08,805
I...

369
00:33:11,246 --> 00:33:12,770
What, Mom?

370
00:33:13,015 --> 00:33:15,006
Before your father...

371
00:33:15,217 --> 00:33:16,946
Yeah?

372
00:33:17,820 --> 00:33:22,018
- There was this boy.

373
00:33:23,959 --> 00:33:25,426
Did you love him?

374
00:33:26,261 --> 00:33:27,990
Yeah.

375
00:33:33,335 --> 00:33:35,929
Well, why didn't you marry him?

376
00:33:37,306 --> 00:33:41,140
So that you could ask me
this question someday.

377
00:33:51,286 --> 00:33:53,345
Looks smaller.

378
00:33:55,324 --> 00:33:57,554
When did he complete it?

379
00:33:58,594 --> 00:34:01,154
You weren't born yet,
and I was 8.

380
00:34:05,868 --> 00:34:08,928
Corbusier meets Frank Lloyd Wright.

381
00:34:09,638 --> 00:34:12,630
You know, Dad played cards
with both of them.

382
00:34:13,709 --> 00:34:17,167
- Sharing a joint.
- Yeah, well...

383
00:34:17,780 --> 00:34:19,714
Can't swim.

384
00:34:20,082 --> 00:34:23,779
There should be a stairway
down to the water, a porch, a deck.

385
00:34:24,353 --> 00:34:26,821
Here, you're in a...
In a box.

386
00:34:27,022 --> 00:34:30,287
A glass box with a view
to everything that's around you...

387
00:34:30,492 --> 00:34:31,959
...but you can't touch it.

388
00:34:32,161 --> 00:34:36,495
No interconnection
between you and what you're looking at.

389
00:34:36,698 --> 00:34:39,531
I don't know, you know.
He's got this big maple growing...

390
00:34:39,735 --> 00:34:42,727
...right in the middle of the house.
- Containment.

391
00:34:46,141 --> 00:34:49,804
Containment and control.

392
00:34:51,613 --> 00:34:55,640
This house is about ownership,
not connection.

393
00:34:56,251 --> 00:35:00,051
I mean, it's beautiful. Seductive, even.

394
00:35:00,255 --> 00:35:03,224
But it's incomplete.

395
00:35:05,527 --> 00:35:07,358
It was all about him.

396
00:35:09,031 --> 00:35:11,431
Dad knew how to build a house,
not a home.

397
00:35:12,434 --> 00:35:13,765
But you know...

398
00:35:14,503 --> 00:35:16,937
...I think he wants us to do
what he couldn't.

399
00:35:17,639 --> 00:35:19,732
But admitting that...

400
00:35:20,442 --> 00:35:24,503
...would mean admitting
that he came up short in some way...

401
00:35:24,713 --> 00:35:26,578
...that he could do more.

402
00:35:26,782 --> 00:35:28,841
And that tortures him.

403
00:35:30,185 --> 00:35:32,676
Do you remember
being here with Mom?

404
00:35:39,528 --> 00:35:41,587
I remember she tried
to make it work here...

405
00:35:42,865 --> 00:35:44,730
...with us...

406
00:35:45,367 --> 00:35:46,959
...with him.

407
00:35:49,104 --> 00:35:50,765
Hey, what about Visionary Vanguard?

408
00:35:50,939 --> 00:35:53,567
- What about it?
- Come on.

409
00:35:53,742 --> 00:35:57,610
You can't convince me you're gonna
be happy building saltboxes for tourists.

410
00:35:58,113 --> 00:36:00,377
Nobody's gonna admire you for that.

411
00:36:00,582 --> 00:36:03,642
- Admire me for that?
- Yeah, Visionary Vanguard.

412
00:36:04,419 --> 00:36:06,410
That's your idea.

413
00:36:06,622 --> 00:36:08,453
I can't. But you can keep the name.

414
00:36:08,624 --> 00:36:10,785
No, come on.
It's gotta be you and me.

415
00:36:10,993 --> 00:36:13,757
Henry, I'm sorry, I can't.

416
00:36:13,962 --> 00:36:15,452
I just...

417
00:36:15,697 --> 00:36:18,894
- What?
- I've got other plans.

418
00:36:19,067 --> 00:36:21,092
You have a girlfriend?

419
00:36:22,938 --> 00:36:23,996
No...

420
00:36:24,173 --> 00:36:25,936
No.

421
00:36:26,308 --> 00:36:29,436
- What is that? You hesitated.
- No, I didn't hesitate.

422
00:36:31,246 --> 00:36:33,646
Come on, man.
I don't have any time for that.

423
00:36:35,150 --> 00:36:37,209
What does time have to do with it?

424
00:36:37,986 --> 00:36:40,352
Oh, you're gonna think I'm crazy.

425
00:36:45,294 --> 00:36:47,728
<i>My dearest Mr. Wyler:</i>

426
00:36:47,930 --> 00:36:50,660
<i>Are you willing to play a game
with me?</i>

427
00:36:51,300 --> 00:36:54,531
<i>Two years ago today,
I was taking the 145 train to Madison...</i>

428
00:36:54,770 --> 00:36:58,137
<i>... from the Riverside station
and I forgot something there.</i>

429
00:36:58,340 --> 00:37:00,865
<i>It was a gift from my father.</i>

430
00:37:01,343 --> 00:37:05,336
<i>If you find it,
can you please put it in the mailbox?</i>

431
00:37:06,348 --> 00:37:08,475
<i>It would mean a lot.</i>

432
00:37:08,784 --> 00:37:12,015
<i>Yours, Kate.</i>

433
00:37:27,769 --> 00:37:32,763
- Final call for the 5:46 to Madison.
- Do you really wanna know? Come on.

434
00:37:32,975 --> 00:37:35,170
- All aboard.
- Okay.

435
00:37:45,287 --> 00:37:46,879
I'll call you.

436
00:38:28,196 --> 00:38:31,563
<i>Kate, I found it. I have it with me.</i>

437
00:38:31,767 --> 00:38:34,463
<i>One day I'll get it to you. Trust me.</i>

438
00:38:34,703 --> 00:38:37,695
<i>I know how important it is to you.</i>

439
00:38:38,974 --> 00:38:42,410
<i>You might not remember,
but we saw each other.</i>

440
00:38:42,611 --> 00:38:44,704
<i>At least, I saw you.</i>

441
00:38:45,947 --> 00:38:50,111
<i>You never told me
how beautiful you are.</i>

442
00:38:50,352 --> 00:38:52,843
<i>Well, maybe you saw somebody else.</i>

443
00:38:53,055 --> 00:38:55,546
<i>That was a bad hair year for me.</i>

444
00:38:55,757 --> 00:38:59,090
<i>Long brown hair.
Gentle, unguarded eyes.</i>

445
00:38:59,294 --> 00:39:01,159
<i>Okay, okay, okay.</i>

446
00:39:01,396 --> 00:39:03,227
<i>You saw me.</i>

447
00:39:03,899 --> 00:39:06,060
<i>But I still don't know
what you look like.</i>

448
00:39:07,636 --> 00:39:11,094
<i>Well, why don't we just get together
in the future...</i>

449
00:39:11,306 --> 00:39:13,968
<i>... and you can let me know
what you think.</i>

450
00:39:14,943 --> 00:39:16,740
It's a date.

451
00:39:19,948 --> 00:39:21,438
Okay.

452
00:39:21,650 --> 00:39:25,984
Why don't you call me
July 10th, 2006...

453
00:39:26,188 --> 00:39:31,421
...at 9:05 p.m.

454
00:39:46,108 --> 00:39:48,474
<i>- Hello.
- Kate?</i>

455
00:39:48,677 --> 00:39:51,510
<i>- Yes.
- It's Morgan.</i>

456
00:39:54,416 --> 00:39:56,008
Morgan.

457
00:39:56,218 --> 00:39:59,119
<i>I'm in Chicago. I came for a meeting,
but it was canceled...</i>

458
00:39:59,321 --> 00:40:01,050
<i>... so I thought I'd give you a call.</i>

459
00:40:01,857 --> 00:40:03,984
Hey, have you eaten?

460
00:40:04,192 --> 00:40:07,684
- No, but I'm not...
- Neither have I. I realized I'm starving.

461
00:40:07,929 --> 00:40:10,489
- We could grab a quick bite.
- Okay.

462
00:40:10,699 --> 00:40:12,564
- Yeah?
- All right.

463
00:40:12,801 --> 00:40:16,430
- Hey, wait up.
- Watch out, man.

464
00:40:16,738 --> 00:40:19,502
- All right.
- Looks pretty good.

465
00:40:19,708 --> 00:40:21,175
- Perfect.
- No, Morgan, it's...

466
00:40:21,376 --> 00:40:22,707
- It's not.
- No, no, trust me.

467
00:40:22,944 --> 00:40:25,412
It's... Okay.

468
00:40:26,882 --> 00:40:28,144
Hi there.

469
00:40:28,350 --> 00:40:30,511
One sec.
Could you hold on for a moment?

470
00:40:30,685 --> 00:40:33,085
- We'd love a table for two.
