00:59:26,581 --> 00:59:27,570
It was you.

724
00:59:27,782 --> 00:59:30,148
- You working tomorrow night?
- Yeah.

725
00:59:30,351 --> 00:59:32,285
Why didn't you say anything?

726
00:59:32,486 --> 00:59:36,388
You would've thought
I was crazy or drunk. Or both.

727
00:59:36,624 --> 00:59:38,353
Yeah, but...

728
00:59:39,126 --> 00:59:41,526
...I liked you.
You should have said something.

729
00:59:41,729 --> 00:59:44,596
How? You were with your boyfriend.

730
00:59:44,799 --> 00:59:47,700
You know what? Excuses, excuses.
You are a coward.

731
00:59:47,902 --> 00:59:49,802
I'm not a coward.

732
00:59:50,004 --> 00:59:53,906
Oh, really?
Well, what about your girlfriend?

733
00:59:54,408 --> 00:59:56,239
What? I told you already...

734
00:59:56,477 --> 00:59:59,605
...she's not my girlfriend.
- He's not my boyfriend either.

735
00:59:59,847 --> 01:00:03,510
Oh, really? Well, what is he, then?
Your brother?

736
01:00:04,385 --> 01:00:09,322
We have a comedian. What'd you have,
a clown for breakfast this morning?

737
01:00:10,992 --> 01:00:13,051
Wonderful. Our first fight.

738
01:00:13,260 --> 01:00:17,219
You could write a song about it
and go sing it in San Francisco.

739
01:00:21,502 --> 01:00:23,265
What?

740
01:00:23,671 --> 01:00:25,138
Hello.

741
01:00:25,339 --> 01:00:27,273
Hey, Henry.

742
01:00:28,709 --> 01:00:30,040
What?

743
01:00:30,211 --> 01:00:32,076
You'll let me know if you need anything?

744
01:00:32,279 --> 01:00:34,076
Yes, I will.

745
01:00:35,416 --> 01:00:36,405
- Hi.
- Good afternoon.

746
01:00:36,651 --> 01:00:40,382
I'm looking for my father. I don't know
which room he's in. Simon Wyler?

747
01:00:40,588 --> 01:00:43,386
- Mr. Wyler, the architect?
- Yes.

748
01:00:43,591 --> 01:00:46,719
I'm Anna Klyczynski.
I'm the Attending for your father.

749
01:00:46,927 --> 01:00:49,088
Hey. What happened? How is he?

750
01:00:49,296 --> 01:00:53,790
He's okay. He's had a heart attack.
Fortunately, relatively minor.

751
01:00:54,035 --> 01:00:57,198
His vitals are fine and he's stable...

752
01:00:57,371 --> 01:00:59,464
...but it will require an intervention.

753
01:00:59,707 --> 01:01:02,733
He's agreed to schedule it
for tomorrow.

754
01:01:17,758 --> 01:01:20,454
Good to see you're taking it easy.

755
01:01:21,262 --> 01:01:25,323
Well, you... You didn't need to come.
I'm perfectly well.

756
01:01:25,700 --> 01:01:27,759
Perfectly all right.

757
01:01:27,968 --> 01:01:30,402
Well, you had a heart attack, Dad.

758
01:01:30,604 --> 01:01:33,937
I had an episode, for chrissake.

759
01:01:34,141 --> 01:01:36,075
Nothing more.

760
01:01:36,777 --> 01:01:40,110
Appreciate it if you kept everything
in its perspective.

761
01:01:42,316 --> 01:01:45,717
Well then, I just wanna let you know
I'm here if you need anything.

762
01:01:47,855 --> 01:01:49,652
Coffee.

763
01:01:50,091 --> 01:01:51,786
What?

764
01:01:52,226 --> 01:01:54,023
You heard me.

765
01:01:56,430 --> 01:01:58,261
Coffee.

766
01:02:00,101 --> 01:02:02,331
<i>There's something
I never told you, Kate.</i>

767
01:02:02,536 --> 01:02:05,004
<i>You see, it was my father
who built the lake house.</i>

768
01:02:05,239 --> 01:02:08,265
<i>I mean, with his own hands.</i>

769
01:02:08,476 --> 01:02:11,309
<i>And it was a long time ago,
before he was famous...</i>

770
01:02:11,512 --> 01:02:14,743
<i>... when he still had a family
and worshipped my mother.</i>

771
01:02:14,949 --> 01:02:18,749
<i>Her name was Mary,
and the house was a gift for her.</i>

772
01:02:18,953 --> 01:02:21,786
<i>She was smart and funny.</i>

773
01:02:21,989 --> 01:02:25,652
<i>She could have done anything, but chose
to take care of my brother and I...</i>

774
01:02:25,860 --> 01:02:27,657
<i>... and help him build his career.</i>

775
01:02:27,862 --> 01:02:31,889
<i>You see, the more successful he became,
the more impossible he was to live with.</i>

776
01:02:32,133 --> 01:02:35,694
<i>Finally, she just couldn't take
living with him anymore.</i>

777
01:02:35,903 --> 01:02:38,838
<i>She left him.</i>

778
01:02:39,039 --> 01:02:41,166
<i>Within a year, she got sick.</i>

779
01:02:41,375 --> 01:02:45,038
<i>Unfortunately, she never learned
how to stop loving him.</i>

780
01:02:46,280 --> 01:02:48,680
<i>He wasn't at the funeral.</i>

781
01:02:50,017 --> 01:02:52,281
<i>When I asked him why...</i>

782
01:02:58,025 --> 01:03:00,823
Go on, Alex. What did he say?

783
01:03:04,799 --> 01:03:08,530
He said, "She was dead to me the
moment she stepped out of the house."

784
01:03:11,539 --> 01:03:15,839
And then he gave me
one of his architect-of-the-year grins.

785
01:03:30,858 --> 01:03:32,120
I hope you appreciate this.

786
01:03:32,359 --> 01:03:35,089
I had to sneak past
three nurses and your Attending.

787
01:03:35,329 --> 01:03:37,627
Oh, jeez, it's hot.

788
01:03:37,965 --> 01:03:39,364
It's not decaf, is it?

789
01:03:39,567 --> 01:03:41,432
It should be, but it isn't.

790
01:03:45,139 --> 01:03:47,767
That's not bad. Thank you...

791
01:03:47,975 --> 01:03:49,602
<i>: : :son:</i>

792
01:03:49,844 --> 01:03:52,938
- You're welcome.
- Where's your brother?

793
01:03:53,113 --> 01:03:55,240
I sent him away.
He wasn't feeling well.

794
01:03:55,449 --> 01:03:58,350
- You know how he is, he worries.
- Yeah, I know.

795
01:03:58,552 --> 01:04:00,645
He gets that from your mother,
I'm afraid.

796
01:04:01,422 --> 01:04:02,889
She always worried too much.

797
01:04:03,090 --> 01:04:04,785
What are you looking at?

798
01:04:05,593 --> 01:04:07,390
Oh, yeah, here, take a gander.

799
01:04:07,595 --> 01:04:10,962
It's a proposal for a museum.

800
01:04:11,165 --> 01:04:14,362
- Who is it?
- Someone new.

801
01:04:15,269 --> 01:04:18,568
Oh, I like the walkways,
where the light falls.

802
01:04:18,772 --> 01:04:20,399
What are the materials?

803
01:04:20,808 --> 01:04:22,799
Granite. Aluminum.

804
01:04:23,010 --> 01:04:25,478
White panels
are straight out of Meier...

805
01:04:25,679 --> 01:04:30,013
...but the interior color coming through
the front windows, that's different.

806
01:04:30,851 --> 01:04:34,184
It's not new,
but it's clean, uncluttered.

807
01:04:34,421 --> 01:04:36,116
I like it.

808
01:04:36,690 --> 01:04:39,750
When was the last time
you were in Barcelona?

809
01:04:41,528 --> 01:04:43,996
Years ago, with you, Mom and Henry.

810
01:04:44,198 --> 01:04:46,826
Do you remember visiting
Casa de la Caritat?

811
01:04:48,002 --> 01:04:49,629
The almshouse.

812
01:04:49,837 --> 01:04:52,305
That's right. You mentioned Meier.

813
01:04:52,506 --> 01:04:57,409
His Barcelona museum stands
in the same area as Casa de la Caritat.

814
01:04:57,611 --> 01:04:59,602
It drinks the same light.

815
01:04:59,813 --> 01:05:04,716
Meier designed a series of louvered
skylights to capture that light...

816
01:05:04,952 --> 01:05:09,719
...and cast it inward to illuminate
the art within, but indirectly.

817
01:05:09,957 --> 01:05:14,951
And that was important,
because although light enhances art...

818
01:05:15,162 --> 01:05:19,963
...it can also degrade it. But you know
all that already, you son of a gun.

819
01:05:20,134 --> 01:05:22,034
Now, this...

820
01:05:23,971 --> 01:05:25,996
...where do you suppose
this is to be built?

821
01:05:26,173 --> 01:05:27,231
I have no idea.

822
01:05:27,408 --> 01:05:29,842
- Oh, but you said you liked it.
- Conceptually.

823
01:05:30,010 --> 01:05:32,240
Now, come on.

824
01:05:32,479 --> 01:05:35,141
You know as well as I do
that the light in Barcelona...

825
01:05:35,349 --> 01:05:37,715
...is quite different
from the light in Tokyo.

826
01:05:37,885 --> 01:05:40,979
And the light in Tokyo
is different from that in Prague.

827
01:05:41,188 --> 01:05:47,184
A truly great structure, one that
is meant to stand the tests of time...

828
01:05:47,394 --> 01:05:49,885
...never disregards its environment.

829
01:05:50,097 --> 01:05:51,894
An architect takes that into account.

830
01:05:52,099 --> 01:05:56,832
He knows that if he wants presence,
he must consult with nature.

831
01:05:57,037 --> 01:06:01,440
He must be captivated by the light.

832
01:06:01,608 --> 01:06:05,339
Always the light. Always.

833
01:07:00,934 --> 01:07:03,232
Hey. I have an emergency.
Take my shift. Please.

834
01:07:08,242 --> 01:07:09,766
Hello.

835
01:07:09,977 --> 01:07:12,605
<i>- Mr. Wyler?
- Yes.</i>

836
01:07:12,813 --> 01:07:16,010
<i>This is Dr. Klyczynski
at Chicago City Hospital.</i>

837
01:07:16,750 --> 01:07:20,242
<i>I'm afraid I have some
difficult news for you.</i>

838
01:07:23,057 --> 01:07:25,617
<i>I'm so sorry, Alex.</i>

839
01:07:26,860 --> 01:07:29,954
<i>I wish somehow
I could be there with you...</i>

840
01:07:30,497 --> 01:07:34,194
<i>... that we could sit together and look
out over the water and the light...</i>

841
01:07:34,435 --> 01:07:37,336
<i>... in this house your father built.</i>

842
01:07:40,340 --> 01:07:43,207
<i>I could be a shoulder for you
like you've been for me.</i>

843
01:07:43,444 --> 01:07:46,572
<i>And tell you that
everything is gonna be okay.</i>

844
01:07:48,482 --> 01:07:51,315
<i>If I could do one thing for you today...</i>

845
01:07:51,518 --> 01:07:53,577
<i>... from here...</i>

846
01:07:53,787 --> 01:07:57,382
<i>... one small, simple thing
from the future...</i>

847
01:07:57,991 --> 01:07:59,982
<i>... I hope this is it.</i>

848
01:08:01,395 --> 01:08:04,125
<i>It won't be published
for a couple of years...</i>

849
01:08:04,331 --> 01:08:06,993
<i>... but I don't think
you should have to wait that long.</i>

850
01:08:08,702 --> 01:08:11,671
<i>I hope it helps you know
how much you were loved.</i>

851
01:09:56,109 --> 01:09:58,509
Pick a place. I'll be there, I promise.

852
01:09:58,745 --> 01:10:00,076
Tomorrow, what do you say?

853
01:10:00,280 --> 01:10:02,111
But, Alex,
it won't be tomorrow for you.

854
01:10:02,316 --> 01:10:05,717
- You're gonna have to wait two years.
- I know, I don't care. I'll wait.

855
01:10:05,919 --> 01:10:07,250
Are you sure? I don't know.

856
01:10:07,454 --> 01:10:09,922
I do. I've never been so sure
of anything in my life.

857
01:10:10,123 --> 01:10:13,251
Okay. I'll see you in two years, then.

858
01:10:13,460 --> 01:10:15,724
See you tomorrow, then.

859
01:10:16,129 --> 01:10:17,824
Kate...

860
01:10:18,031 --> 01:10:20,022
...where would you like to go?

861
01:10:22,836 --> 01:10:24,497
II Mare.

862
01:10:24,671 --> 01:10:26,662
When were you hoping
to dine with us?

863
01:10:26,873 --> 01:10:28,465
Two years from tomorrow.

864
01:10:28,675 --> 01:10:30,836
- Two years from tomorrow?
- Yeah.

865
01:10:31,044 --> 01:10:33,012
- Two years?
- From tomorrow.

866
01:10:34,982 --> 01:10:36,973
- Hi.
- Hello. Name?

867
01:10:37,150 --> 01:10:38,276
Forster.

868
01:10:38,452 --> 01:10:39,817
- Can I have your name?
- Wyler.

869
01:10:39,987 --> 01:10:42,547
Or Wyler, I'm...
I'm really not sure.

870
01:10:42,723 --> 01:10:44,953
I think we should be able
to accommodate you.

871
01:10:45,158 --> 01:10:46,216
- Great.
- Wyler?

872
01:10:48,395 --> 01:10:49,885
Wyler.

873
01:10:51,531 --> 01:10:53,999
Your waiter will be right with you.

874
01:11:18,158 --> 01:11:20,319
Good evening, miss.

875
01:11:21,995 --> 01:11:24,429
Complimentary.

876
01:11:34,708 --> 01:11:37,541
- Thank you.
- Good luck.

877
01:12:00,200 --> 01:12:02,566
Another glass for the lady?

878
01:13:30,223 --> 01:13:32,316
<i>You weren't there.</i>

879
01:13:32,659 --> 01:13:34,854
<i>You didn't come.</i>

880
01:13:41,234 --> 01:13:43,031
I don't understand.

881
01:13:43,236 --> 01:13:46,364
<i>Something must have happened.
I'm sorry.</i>

882
01:13:46,573 --> 01:13:49,440
<i>I've got two years, Kate.
We can try again.</i>

883
01:13:49,643 --> 01:13:53,875
<i>No, Alex, it's too late.</i>

884
01:13:54,080 --> 01:13:57,675
<i>It already happened. It didn't work.</i>

885
01:13:57,884 --> 01:13:59,818
<i>Don't give up on me, Kate.</i>

886
01:14:00,020 --> 01:14:03,717
<i>What about Persuasion?
You told me. They wait.</i>

887
01:14:03,957 --> 01:14:05,982
<i>They meet again,
they have another chance.</i>

888
01:14:06,193 --> 01:14:08,320
<i>Life is not a book, Alex.</i>

889
01:14:08,528 --> 01:14:11,019
<i>And it can be over in a second.</i>

890
01:14:11,231 --> 01:14:14,598
<i>I was having lunch with my mother
at Daley Plaza...</i>

891
01:14:14,835 --> 01:14:17,565
<i>... and a man was killed
right in front of me.</i>

892
01:14:17,771 --> 01:14:20,001
<i>He died in my arms.</i>

893
01:14:20,207 --> 01:14:21,731
<i>And I thought:</i>

894
01:14:21,975 --> 01:14:26,241
<i>"It can't end just like that
on Valentine's Day. "</i>

895
01:14:27,180 --> 01:14:30,172
<i>I thought about all the people
who love him, waiting at home...</i>

896
01:14:30,383 --> 01:14:32,874
<i>... who will never see him again.</i>

897
01:14:33,787 --> 01:14:35,721
<i>And then I thought:</i>

898
01:14:35,922 --> 01:14:38,254
<i>"What if there is no one?"</i>

899
01:14:39,059 --> 01:14:44,554
<i>What if you live your whole life
and no one is waiting?</i>

900
01:14:45,065 --> 01:14:49,001
<i>So I drove to the lake house
looking for any kind of answer.</i>

901
01:14:49,202 --> 01:14:51,602
<i>And I found you.</i>

902
01:14:51,805 --> 01:14:54,239
<i>And I let myself get lost.</i>

903
01:14:54,441 --> 01:14:59,811
<i>Lost in this beautiful fantasy
where time stood still.</i>

904
01:15:00,280 --> 01:15:02,646
<i>But it's not real, Alex.</i>

905
01:15:02,883 --> 01:15:07,820
<i>I have to learn to live
the life that I have got.</i>

906
01:15:09,422 --> 01:15:11,617
<i>Please don't write anymore.</i>

907
01:15:11,825 --> 01:15:14,123
<i>Don't try to find me.</i>

908
01:15:15,061 --> 01:15:17,723
<i>Let me let you go.</i>

909
01:16:05,111 --> 01:16:06,942
Hello.

910
01:16:07,714 --> 01:16:10,649
What? Sorry, hold on.
I can't hear you. I'll be back, sorry.

911
01:16:10,850 --> 01:16:13,512
Hello. Hold on. Hold on.

912
01:16:13,954 --> 01:16:15,649
Hello.

913
01:16:16,882 --> 01:16:18,645
Hi.

914
01:16:25,498 --> 01:16:27,693
How long are you here?

915
01:16:30,904 --> 01:16:34,237
- I'm at a bar with some friends.
- Come.

916
01:16:34,474 --> 01:16:37,034
Well, don't get too excited.

917
01:16:38,478 --> 01:16:41,038
I find that hard to believe.

918
01:16:43,016 --> 01:16:44,483
It is good.

919
01:16:44,684 --> 01:16:47,676
And it was really good
to hear your voice.

920
01:16:47,887 --> 01:16:51,220
I was surprised how good
it was to hear your voice.

921
01:16:54,361 --> 01:16:55,851
So how was your meeting?

922
01:16:56,062 --> 01:16:58,189
- It was good.
- Yeah?

923
01:16:58,398 --> 01:17:01,231
Yeah, l... I got the job.

924
01:17:01,434 --> 01:17:03,766
- Really?
- Yeah.

925
01:17:04,204 --> 01:17:06,365
- Well, congratulations.
- Imagine that.

926
01:17:06,573 --> 01:17:12,205
Yeah. A telecom company.
I'll be in-house counsel. Pays well.

927
01:17:12,412 --> 01:17:14,505
And it's here...

928
01:17:14,714 --> 01:17:16,181
...in Chicago.

929
01:17:17,017 --> 01:17:18,746
Well...

930
01:17:18,952 --> 01:17:21,045
...it's great news.

931
01:17:23,423 --> 01:17:25,220
Hey.

932
01:17:29,195 --> 01:17:30,890
What?

933
01:17:51,084 --> 01:17:52,574
Jack.

934
01:17:52,786 --> 01:17:54,720
Hey, Jack.

935
01:17:55,055 --> 01:17:56,818
Jack.

936
01:19:17,270 --> 01:19:19,534
Are you gonna
come down this weekend?

937
01:19:21,708 --> 01:19:23,903
Don't you miss me a little bit?

938
01:19:24,577 --> 01:19:27,045
Oh, just a little bit. Not a lot, huh?

939
01:19:27,514 --> 01:19:31,177
Okay. No, I heard you. Yeah.

940
01:19:33,052 --> 01:19:36,317
Kate, I'm gonna
have to call you back, okay?

941
01:19:51,171 --> 01:19:53,605
Still wanna rent a lake house?

942
01:19:54,541 --> 01:19:56,873
It's what Kate wants.

943
01:19:57,076 --> 01:19:59,670
How the hell do you know
what Kate wants?

944
01:20:01,047 --> 01:20:02,708
Trust me.

945
01:20:14,594 --> 01:20:17,722
Hey, you. I know you.

946
01:20:24,070 --> 01:20:26,766
Whatever you want out back.

947
01:20:56,669 --> 01:20:58,500
What do you think?

948
01:20:59,105 --> 01:21:01,232
You're fixating. You know?

949
01:21:02,275 --> 01:21:04,106
Why do you keep
tweaking the lake house?

950
01:21:04,310 --> 01:21:06,403
Why don't you do your own work?

951
01:21:06,579 --> 01:21:08,809
Because it's hers.

952
01:21:09,182 --> 01:21:14,449
You're talking about the girl
from the future.

953
01:21:14,654 --> 01:21:16,315
Kate.

954
01:21:17,156 --> 01:21:19,920
And you're still writing with Kate?

955
01:21:20,293 --> 01:21:23,660
- No.
- Why not?

956
01:21:25,131 --> 01:21:26,689
She asked me not to.

957
01:21:27,400 --> 01:21:29,095
Why?

958
01:21:31,404 --> 01:21:33,099
Time.

959
01:21:37,010 --> 01:21:38,534
Hey, come on.

960
01:21:38,778 --> 01:21:42,509
This is a good thing.
You know, you need a real woman.

961
01:21:42,715 --> 01:21:45,809
- A woman...
- Henry, listen.

962
01:21:47,020 --> 01:21:48,817
Listen to me.

963
01:21:49,289 --> 01:21:54,283
While it lasted, she was
more real to me than any of that stuff.

964
01:21:54,494 --> 01:21:58,624
She was more real to me
than anything I've ever known.

965
01:22:00,833 --> 01:22:02,664
I saw her.

966
01:22:03,536 --> 01:22:05,367
I kissed her.

967
01:22:07,740 --> 01:22:09,367
I love her.

968
01:22:12,545 --> 01:22:14,638
And now she's gone.

969
01:22:23,556 --> 01:22:25,319
She's gone.

970
01:22:32,732 --> 01:22:34,359
<i>And Duckett squirts through.</i>

971
01:22:34,867 --> 01:22:36,562
<i>First thing...</i>

972
01:22:38,104 --> 01:22:40,470
<i>How could the Ab Scissor
four-minute ab machine...?</i>

973
01:22:40,673 --> 01:22:43,335
<i>- and your potatoes
cooking on the top.</i>

974
01:22:43,543 --> 01:22:47,104
<i>It's nice out here. Let's stay here.</i>

975
01:22:47,347 --> 01:22:49,212
<i>But we have to eat.</i>

976
01:22:50,216 --> 01:22:53,413
<i>We can eat here. I'll cook.</i>

977
01:22:53,786 --> 01:22:56,050
<i>I thought you didn't like to cook.</i>

978
01:22:56,689 --> 01:22:58,987
<i>No, I don't like to cook.</i>

979
01:23:00,626 --> 01:23:03,925
<i>But I have a chicken in the icebox,
and you're eating it.</i>

980
01:23:04,130 --> 01:23:06,257
<i>What about all
the washing-up afterward?</i>

981
01:23:06,499 --> 01:23:09,059
<i>- We'll eat with our fingers.
- Could you turn that down?</i>

982
01:23:09,268 --> 01:23:10,701
<i>Don't we need any plates?</i>

983
01:23:10,903 --> 01:23:14,600
<i>Yes. One for you,
and one for...</i>

984
01:24:26,212 --> 01:24:29,648
"There could have been
no two hearts so open...

985
01:24:30,316 --> 01:24:33,114
...no tastes so similar...

986
01:24:34,320 --> 01:24:37,221
...no feelings so in unison."

987
01:24:51,804 --> 01:24:56,639
Ten, nine, eight, seven, six...

988
01:24:56,843 --> 01:25:01,337
...five, four, three, two, one.

989
01:25:01,547 --> 01:25:04,414
Happy New Year!

990
01:25:16,996 --> 01:25:18,759
Come in.

991
01:25:32,337 --> 01:25:33,964
Hi.

992
01:25:34,472 --> 01:25:35,962
Hi.

993
01:25:38,784 --> 01:25:40,217
What do you think?

994
01:25:40,419 --> 01:25:42,284
This is what I gave up lunch for?

995
01:25:42,522 --> 01:25:47,255
- I know it needs work.
- Work? How about a wrecking ball?

996
01:25:47,560 --> 01:25:50,586
I found an architect
who specializes in renovations.

997
01:25:50,796 --> 01:25:53,230
I made an appointment for tomorrow.

998
01:25:57,737 --> 01:25:59,295
Ambush.

999
01:25:59,539 --> 01:26:00,801
Come on.

1000
01:26:01,040 --> 01:26:04,532
We can't stay in my apartment.
We've been there over a year.

1001
01:26:05,678 --> 01:26:07,407
I wanna keep moving forward.

1002
01:26:17,990 --> 01:26:21,289
- It's a new firm.
- "New" as in inexperienced?

1003
01:26:21,494 --> 01:26:24,258
No. "New" as in cheap.

1004
01:26:34,473 --> 01:26:36,839
Hi, Dr. Forster.
We'll be with you in a moment.

1005
01:26:37,076 --> 01:26:38,771
Great, thank you.

1006
01:26:52,525 --> 01:26:55,619
Oh, by the way...

1007
01:26:57,029 --> 01:26:59,156
...happy Valentine's Day.

1008
01:26:59,365 --> 01:27:02,493
Oh, God, Katie,
I didn't get you anything.

1009
01:27:02,735 --> 01:27:05,863
I'm sorry. I've just been
so swamped and...

1010
01:27:06,105 --> 01:27:08,005
Doesn't matter.

1011
01:27:24,523 --> 01:27:28,289
- What is this?
- It's global warming.

1012
01:27:30,529 --> 01:27:34,522
Dr. Forster?
Hi, I'm sorry to have kept you waiting.

1013
01:27:53,319 --> 01:27:55,753
- Hi. Good to see you again.
- Dr. Forster. You too.

1014
01:27:55,988 --> 01:27:58,889
- Hi, I'm Morgan.
- Hey, Morgan. Vanessa Vanderbeck.

1015
01:27:59,091 --> 01:28:03,391
So obviously, the first thing you see
is what we had talked about. The atrium.

1016
01:28:04,096 --> 01:28:05,495
That's stunning.

1017
01:28:05,665 --> 01:28:09,192
So we were able to do it with all
the glass panels in the metal structure?

1018
01:28:09,402 --> 01:28:10,994
- Yeah.
- Can l...?

1019
01:28:11,270 --> 01:28:12,567
Wanna get a beer after work?

1020
01:28:12,805 --> 01:28:16,866
I'm sorry, I can't. I'm taking
Vanessa out for Valentine's Day.

1021
01:28:20,579 --> 01:28:22,069
Wait.

1022
01:28:22,615 --> 01:28:24,048
Say that again.

1023
01:28:24,250 --> 01:28:27,378
It's Valentine's Day today.
I'm taking out Vanessa, my girlfriend.

1024
01:28:27,586 --> 01:28:30,953
Cold champagne, some oysters,
maybe a little chocolate.

1025
01:28:31,190 --> 01:28:34,682
- What's the date?
- It's February 14th.

1026
01:28:35,594 --> 01:28:39,860
- February 14th, 2006.
- Yeah.

1027
01:28:40,466 --> 01:28:43,333
- Stunning. Thank you so much.
- Our pleasure.

1028
01:28:43,536 --> 01:28:45,970
Thank you. Henry will
make sure you have everything.

1029
01:28:46,205 --> 01:28:48,105
Great. They were absolutely beautiful.

1030
01:28:48,341 --> 01:28:49,831
Thank you.

1031
01:28:51,110 --> 01:28:52,600
What?

1032
01:28:54,080 --> 01:28:57,379
Katie, I gotta get back to work.

1033
01:29:00,353 --> 01:29:02,218
Who did this drawing?

1034
01:29:02,421 --> 01:29:04,548
My brother did, actually.

1035
01:29:04,724 --> 01:29:06,089
Who's your brother?

1036
01:29:06,292 --> 01:29:08,283
Alex Wyler.

1037
01:29:08,594 --> 01:29:10,357
Did you know him?

1038
01:29:12,498 --> 01:29:14,056
Yeah.

1039
01:29:15,000 --> 01:29:16,763
Yeah, I know him.

1040
01:29:19,271 --> 01:29:21,466
Do you know how
I can get in touch with him?

1041
01:29:21,674 --> 01:29:24,575
Is he...?
Is he anywhere that I can?

1042
01:29:27,279 --> 01:29:29,144
I'm sorry.

1043
01:29:29,782 --> 01:29:33,809
He died...

1044
01:29:34,286 --> 01:29:36,982
...two years ago today, actually.

1045
01:29:40,292 --> 01:29:42,385
There was an accident.

1046
01:30:00,045 --> 01:30:01,637
Where?

1047
01:30:05,317 --> 01:30:06,807
Kate.

1048
01:30:09,188 --> 01:30:11,622
Wait, just stop. Just stop.

1049
01:30:12,124 --> 01:30:14,217
Goddamn it, answer me.

1050
01:30:14,527 --> 01:30:18,554
What is the matter? Kate.

1051
01:30:21,233 --> 01:30:22,791
Kate!

1052
01:31:27,233 --> 01:31:30,259
Sixty degrees on Valentine's Day.

1053
01:31:30,503 --> 01:31:32,801
This cannot be Chicago.

1054
01:31:33,205 --> 01:31:36,231
The TV says it's global warming.

1055
01:31:36,609 --> 01:31:38,372
Nothing wrong with that.

1056
01:31:38,577 --> 01:31:40,306
It's a dangerous thing.

1057
01:31:40,746 --> 01:31:42,441
<i>Alex...</i>

1058
01:31:43,883 --> 01:31:46,784
<i>... I know why you
didn't show up that night.</i>

1059
01:31:47,019 --> 01:31:50,284
<i>It was you at Daley Plaza that day.</i>

1060
01:31:51,457 --> 01:31:53,254
<i>It was you.</i>

1061
01:31:54,159 --> 01:31:56,218
<i>Please, don't go.</i>

1062
01:31:57,296 --> 01:32:00,754
<i>Just wait. Please.</i>

1063
01:32:01,734 --> 01:32:03,099
<i>Don't look for me.</i>

1064
01:32:03,302 --> 01:32:05,634
<i>Don't try to find me.</i>

1065
01:32:07,806 --> 01:32:09,671
<i>I love you.</i>

1066
01:32:12,511 --> 01:32:16,140
<i>And it's taken me all this time
to say it, but I love you.</i>

1067
01:32:23,656 --> 01:32:25,283
<i>And if you still care for me...</i>

1068
01:32:27,159 --> 01:32:29,093
<i>... wait for me.</i>

1069
01:32:29,628 --> 01:32:31,619
<i>Wait with me.</i>

1070
01:32:31,830 --> 01:32:35,322
<i>Just wait. Wait.</i>

1071
01:32:44,076 --> 01:32:46,476
<i>Wait two years, Alex.</i>

1072
01:32:46,946 --> 01:32:49,278
<i>Come to the lake house.</i>

1073
01:32:49,648 --> 01:32:51,479
<i>I'm here.</i>

1074
01:33:48,674 --> 01:33:50,505
You waited.

1075
01:38:29,821 --> 01:38:31,812
[ENGLISH]

